  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 14.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "The sons of Manasseh",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The tribe of Manasseh has been partly treated of in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 5:23-26",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", viz. those of the tribe who inhabited Gilead and Bashan. Here those who inhabited this side Jordan are treated cf. And it is very difficult to give any coherent account of the differences of this passage when compared with ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 26:28-34",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 17:1-4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". In these places six families, or heads of families, are noted to only two, or at most three here, viz. Askriel, Shemida, and perhaps Abiezer (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "iq.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Jeezer, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 26:30",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; comp. with ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 17:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). The opening clause of this verse also is unmanageable as it stands. One way of reducing it to coherence would be to Supply the words \"his wife\" between whom and bars, the similarity of the Hebrew letters of which to those of the Hebrew for \"whom\" might possibly account for the loss of it. The parenthesis about the concubine would then read with emphasis. But there is not the slightest reason to suppose there was such a wife. Another way would be to read the concubine as the mother of Ashriel, and prefix a conjunction, and, to the second \"bare;\" ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "i.e.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
